n, N gains positive charge)\n\nThis is a **hydride transfer** mechanism. The mechanistic class is \"hydride_transfer\".\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the SMIRKS notation, the mapped atoms show:\n- In reactant: [CH+:20] (carbocation) and [C:11]([H:10]) with [N:12]\n- In product: [CH:20]([H:10]) (neutralized) and [C:11]=[N+:12]\n\nThe H:10 moves from C:11 to C:20, and simultaneously C:11-N:12 becomes C:11=N+:12.\n\nThis is indeed a hydride transfer reaction. The mechanistic classification is \"hydride_transfer\".\n\nFor the reaction center, the key atoms involved are: C:20 (carbocation → neutral C), H:10 (transferred), C:11 (loses H, forms double bond with N), N:12 (gains positive charge, forms double bond with C:11).\n\nThe task asks for mechanistic class and reaction center. The expected output schema is \"mechanistic_label\". Let me provide the mechanistic class.\n\nThe mechanistic class is: hydride_transfer"
